text:
Burling Slip, south side, west across Front, to Water Street's. In the right background is the distinctive Singer Building. At the left is the Kuhn, Loeb & Company building (52-4 William Street). The Equitable Building (under construction) is obscured by the New York Mutual Life Insurance Company building and the triangular Great American Insurance Company structure. The New York Steam Company plant replaced the low warehouses on Water Street, at the right.

October, 1914

George L. Balgue
title: Manhattan: Burling Slip - Front Street

text:
Burling Slip, north side, west from Front to Water Streets. Also shown is Front Street, at, adjoining and north of the N.W. corner of Burling Slip.

About 1920.

Edwin Levick.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.
title: Manhattan: Burling Slip - Between Front and Water Streets (West).

text:
Burling Slip, north side, west from Front, to and including Water Streets. Also shown is Front Street, at, adjoining and north of the N.W. corner of Burling Slip.

About 1924.

Edwin Levick.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.
title: Manhattan: Burling Slip - Front Street

text:
(1)

22 to 14 Burling Slip, south side, west from and including Front, to Water Streets. Also shown (left) are Nos. 180 to 174 Front Street, at, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of Burling Slip.

March 27, 1931.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

A detail of the same, showing No. 22 only (bearing also No. 180 Front Street). Note the iron stairway and balcony entrance to the second floor, a quaint remnant of the older types of building construction.

March 27, 1931.

P. L. Sperr.
